<dl id="n38101e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38101e">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38101e"> 101(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Siloa</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Welsh Place-Names]</font> &mdash; A striking peculiarity of the Principality is the prevalence of Scriptural place-names <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Not only are such names as Horeb, Zion, Penuel, <mark>Siloh</mark>, &amp;c., bestowed on Nonconformist chapels, but these Biblical terms have been applied to their surrounding houses, and in not a few instances to growing towns and villages. A notable example of this curious nomenclature occurs in Bethesa, Carnarvonshire <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> <small> &ldquo;WALES&rdquo; <a name="EBWA" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EBWA"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) XXVIII 259</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
